WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:04.425
Many teams begin by choosing a framework, drawing a multi-agent diagram,

2
00:00:04.425 --> 00:00:06.588
and asking several models to debate.

3
00:00:06.538 --> 00:00:10.817
Anthropic found that successful production systems often use simpler,

4
00:00:10.817 --> 00:00:12.057
composable patterns.

5
00:00:12.057 --> 00:00:15.825
Quality depends less on the number of agents than on clear task

6
00:00:15.825 --> 00:00:19.413
boundaries, evaluation criteria, and environmental feedback.

7
00:00:19.413 --> 00:00:23.853
A complex architecture may not improve completion, but it will increase

8
00:00:23.853 --> 00:00:26.480
model calls, latency, cost, and debugging.

9
00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:30.462
Every extra handoff adds another chance to lose context or pass a

10
00:00:30.462 --> 00:00:31.442
mistake forward.

11
00:00:31.442 --> 00:00:34.950
In this video, we will answer three questions that are easy to get

12
00:00:34.950 --> 00:00:38.512
wrong: when one model call is enough, which of five common workflow

13
00:00:38.512 --> 00:00:42.233
patterns fits the task, and when an autonomous agent is actually worth

14
00:00:42.233 --> 00:00:42.711
the risk.

15
00:00:42.711 --> 00:00:46.393
By the end, you will have an Agent Architecture Decision Ladder that you

16
00:00:46.393 --> 00:00:50.074
can use on a real project, instead of paying for complexity just to make

17
00:00:50.074 --> 00:00:51.557
the system look more agentic.

18
00:00:51.700 --> 00:00:55.246
Start with the distinction that controls every later decision.

19
00:00:55.196 --> 00:00:59.138
In a workflow, code defines the execution path in advance.

20
00:00:59.138 --> 00:01:03.167
A model may perform one step, but the program still controls the

21
00:01:03.167 --> 00:01:03.734
sequence.

22
00:01:03.734 --> 00:01:07.526
In an agent, the model uses the current result to choose what to do

23
00:01:07.526 --> 00:01:10.696
next, which tool to call, and when the task should stop.

24
00:01:10.696 --> 00:01:14.772
An expense report that always moves through extraction, policy checks,

25
00:01:14.772 --> 00:01:17.917
and approval has a path you can draw before execution.

26
00:01:17.917 --> 00:01:20.282
That is a strong workflow task.

27
00:01:20.282 --> 00:01:22.926
An incident investigation is different.

28
00:01:22.926 --> 00:01:26.996
You may read logs first, then inspect metrics, and only then decide

29
00:01:26.996 --> 00:01:30.763
whether to investigate the database, the network, or the code.

30
00:01:30.763 --> 00:01:34.869
The path emerges from evidence, so an agent can add real value.

31
00:01:34.869 --> 00:01:37.100
Neither one is more advanced.

32
00:01:37.100 --> 00:01:40.657
Workflows optimize for consistency and predictability.

33
00:01:40.657 --> 00:01:44.648
Agents optimize for flexibility and model-directed decisions.

34
00:01:44.648 --> 00:01:48.456
The most important principle is to find the simplest viable solution and

35
00:01:48.456 --> 00:01:51.946
increase complexity only when the result is measurably inadequate.

36
00:01:51.946 --> 00:01:55.561
Inadequate does not mean the diagram looks unsophisticated.

37
00:01:55.561 --> 00:02:00.428
It means completion rate, accuracy, latency, cost, or human intervention

38
00:02:00.428 --> 00:02:02.051
misses a defined target.

39
00:02:02.051 --> 00:02:05.841
If a new orchestration layer does not help the same evaluation set

40
00:02:05.841 --> 00:02:08.311
finish more reliably, it is not an upgrade.

41
00:02:08.311 --> 00:02:09.830
It is overhead.

42
00:02:09.830 --> 00:02:11.369
Chapter recap.

43
00:02:11.369 --> 00:02:14.628
First, use a workflow when the path is fixed.

44
00:02:14.628 --> 00:02:18.484
Second, use an agent only when the path must be dynamic.

45
00:02:18.484 --> 00:02:22.638
Third, every added layer must earn its place with a measurable result.

46
00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:26.740
Before workflows and agents, there is a more useful default: the

47
00:02:26.740 --> 00:02:28.287
augmented language model.

48
00:02:28.237 --> 00:02:30.372
It is not a team of agents.

49
00:02:30.372 --> 00:02:34.362
It is one model connected to retrieval, tools, and memory.

50
00:02:34.362 --> 00:02:38.437
Retrieval supplies current external facts instead of relying only on

51
00:02:38.437 --> 00:02:39.276
training data.

52
00:02:39.276 --> 00:02:43.969
Tools let the model query an order, read a database, call an API, or

53
00:02:43.969 --> 00:02:45.487
perform a real action.

54
00:02:45.487 --> 00:02:48.478
Memory preserves useful state across steps.

55
00:02:48.478 --> 00:02:52.055
These capabilities answer three different questions: what does the

56
00:02:52.055 --> 00:02:55.199
system know, what can it do, and what has it already done?

57
00:02:55.199 --> 00:02:57.343
Imagine a support assistant.

58
00:02:57.343 --> 00:03:01.414
It retrieves the refund policy, looks up the order, calls the refund

59
00:03:01.414 --> 00:03:04.228
API, and remembers what the customer confirmed.

60
00:03:04.228 --> 00:03:07.914
If order lookup fails, the tool must return the error instead of

61
00:03:07.914 --> 00:03:10.506
inviting the model to invent an order status.

62
00:03:10.506 --> 00:03:15.091
If a refund already ran, stored state and API idempotency must prevent a

63
00:03:15.091 --> 00:03:16.237
duplicate payment.

64
00:03:16.237 --> 00:03:20.458
That single augmented model can already complete many real tasks.

65
00:03:20.458 --> 00:03:23.574
Multiple agents are not automatically necessary.

66
00:03:23.574 --> 00:03:27.180
The key is not to connect as many capabilities as possible.

67
00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:31.705
Each capability must fit the task, expose a clear interface, and be used

68
00:03:31.705 --> 00:03:32.836
at the right time.

69
00:03:32.836 --> 00:03:36.685
Running one augmented model on a controlled task usually reveals whether

70
00:03:36.685 --> 00:03:40.427
the real gap is knowledge, action, or decision-making before you split

71
00:03:40.427 --> 00:03:41.603
the system into roles.

72
00:03:41.603 --> 00:03:43.141
Chapter recap.

73
00:03:43.141 --> 00:03:46.324
First, retrieval provides external facts.

74
00:03:46.324 --> 00:03:49.218
Second, tools perform real actions.

75
00:03:49.218 --> 00:03:51.987
Third, memory preserves task state.

76
00:03:52.132 --> 00:03:55.417
When one model call is not enough but the overall path is still

77
00:03:55.417 --> 00:03:59.120
controllable, choose the workflow pattern that matches the uncertainty.

78
00:03:59.070 --> 00:04:03.246
The first pattern is prompt chaining: split one difficult task into a

79
00:04:03.246 --> 00:04:04.820
sequence of smaller steps.

80
00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:08.481
For example, generate an outline, check it against explicit

81
00:04:08.481 --> 00:04:11.397
requirements, and only then draft the document.

82
00:04:11.397 --> 00:04:15.428
Each step solves one clear problem, and a programmatic gate can stop the

83
00:04:15.428 --> 00:04:17.387
chain when the output is not ready.

84
00:04:17.387 --> 00:04:20.810
Prompt chaining works when the task decomposes cleanly.

85
00:04:20.810 --> 00:04:25.407
It costs more calls and time, but each call becomes easier to evaluate.

86
00:04:25.407 --> 00:04:29.811
The useful part is the gate: if the outline has no audience, rewrite it;

87
00:04:29.811 --> 00:04:33.176
if fact checking fails, do not continue to publication.

88
00:04:33.176 --> 00:04:37.022
Do not let a weak intermediate result travel all the way to the end.

89
00:04:37.022 --> 00:04:39.157
The second pattern is routing.

90
00:04:39.157 --> 00:04:43.566
A router classifies the input and sends it to the right prompt, model,

91
00:04:43.566 --> 00:04:44.070
or tool.

92
00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:48.461
Customer requests might branch into product questions, refund requests,

93
00:04:48.461 --> 00:04:49.945
and technical incidents.

94
00:04:49.945 --> 00:04:54.554
Common cases can use a smaller model, while unusual cases use a stronger

95
00:04:54.554 --> 00:04:54.810
one.

96
00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:58.570
Routing works when categories need clearly different treatment and

97
00:04:58.570 --> 00:05:00.108
classification is reliable.

98
00:05:00.108 --> 00:05:02.608
It also needs a low-confidence path.

99
00:05:02.608 --> 00:05:06.626
An uncertain input should go to a general process or a human, not be

100
00:05:06.626 --> 00:05:08.339
forced into the wrong branch.

101
00:05:08.339 --> 00:05:12.580
The third pattern is parallelization, and it has two distinct forms.

102
00:05:12.580 --> 00:05:16.834
Sectioning runs independent subtasks at the same time and combines the

103
00:05:16.834 --> 00:05:17.320
results.

104
00:05:17.320 --> 00:05:22.148
To evaluate an AI answer, separate reviewers can check facts, safety,

105
00:05:22.148 --> 00:05:24.387
clarity, and format in parallel.

106
00:05:24.387 --> 00:05:28.234
Voting asks several independent attempts to judge the same question,

107
00:05:28.234 --> 00:05:30.157
then aggregates their conclusions.

108
00:05:30.157 --> 00:05:33.934
A security review might use different prompts to inspect the same code

109
00:05:33.934 --> 00:05:35.714
from different risk perspectives.

110
00:05:35.714 --> 00:05:40.014
Parallelization helps when subtasks are independent or when one judgment

111
00:05:40.014 --> 00:05:41.387
is not reliable enough.

112
00:05:41.387 --> 00:05:43.253
Independence matters.

113
00:05:43.253 --> 00:05:47.465
Copying the same prompt three times often creates three versions of the

114
00:05:47.465 --> 00:05:49.897
same bias, not three useful perspectives.

115
00:05:49.897 --> 00:05:52.628
The fourth pattern is orchestrator-workers.

116
00:05:52.628 --> 00:05:56.769
A central model understands the goal, discovers the required subtasks,

117
00:05:56.769 --> 00:05:59.964
delegates them to workers, and combines their results.

118
00:05:59.964 --> 00:06:03.851
The difference from ordinary parallel work is that the subtasks are not

119
00:06:03.851 --> 00:06:04.782
known in advance.

120
00:06:04.782 --> 00:06:07.830
The orchestrator decides them from the current input.

121
00:06:07.830 --> 00:06:10.368
Consider changing a large codebase.

122
00:06:10.368 --> 00:06:14.336
Before investigation, you do not know how many files must change or

123
00:06:14.336 --> 00:06:15.580
which modules matter.

124
00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:19.328
The orchestrator must first inspect the problem, then choose where to

125
00:06:19.328 --> 00:06:21.012
search and what work to assign.

126
00:06:21.012 --> 00:06:25.068
This pattern fits complex tasks that can be divided but cannot be fully

127
00:06:25.068 --> 00:06:25.868
planned ahead.

128
00:06:25.868 --> 00:06:29.819
Each worker still needs only the relevant context and a consistent

129
00:06:29.819 --> 00:06:30.657
return format.

130
00:06:30.657 --> 00:06:34.792
Otherwise, the final synthesis spends most of its budget reinterpreting

131
00:06:34.792 --> 00:06:35.782
scattered output.

132
00:06:35.782 --> 00:06:38.714
The fifth pattern is evaluator-optimizer.

133
00:06:38.714 --> 00:06:43.064
One model generates a result, another evaluates it, and the first model

134
00:06:43.064 --> 00:06:44.964
revises from concrete feedback.

135
00:06:44.964 --> 00:06:49.138
In literary translation, the evaluator can check meaning, tone, and

136
00:06:49.138 --> 00:06:52.253
terminology before proposing specific corrections.

137
00:06:52.253 --> 00:06:56.124
The loop works only when feedback can demonstrably improve the result

138
00:06:56.124 --> 00:06:58.705
and the evaluator can identify useful changes.

139
00:06:58.705 --> 00:07:02.548
It also needs a stopping condition: reach a score, stop after no

140
00:07:02.548 --> 00:07:05.551
improvement, or stop when the budget is exhausted.

141
00:07:05.551 --> 00:07:09.897
Without a clear evaluation standard, the loop only increases cost.

142
00:07:09.897 --> 00:07:12.070
It does not guarantee quality.

143
00:07:12.070 --> 00:07:15.166
The reusable rule is to locate the uncertainty.

144
00:07:15.166 --> 00:07:18.932
Use chaining for fixed steps, routing for different input classes,

145
00:07:18.932 --> 00:07:22.927
parallelization for independent work, orchestrator-workers for runtime

146
00:07:22.927 --> 00:07:26.522
task discovery, and evaluator-optimizer for outputs that can be

147
00:07:26.522 --> 00:07:28.291
explicitly judged and improved.

148
00:07:28.291 --> 00:07:32.497
Patterns can combine, but every addition must solve a named problem, and

149
00:07:32.497 --> 00:07:34.483
every step must remain observable.

150
00:07:34.483 --> 00:07:36.022
Chapter recap.

151
00:07:36.022 --> 00:07:39.378
First, locate where uncertainty enters the task.

152
00:07:39.378 --> 00:07:43.012
Second, choose the workflow that controls that uncertainty.

153
00:07:43.012 --> 00:07:46.820
Third, add a pattern only when it solves a specific problem.

154
00:07:46.900 --> 00:07:50.374
You enter true agent territory when the execution path cannot be

155
00:07:50.374 --> 00:07:54.175
predicted and the model must keep adapting its plan from environmental

156
00:07:54.175 --> 00:07:54.609
results.

157
00:07:54.559 --> 00:07:57.319
The core of an agent is not mysterious.

158
00:07:57.319 --> 00:07:59.540
It is a continuing decision loop.

159
00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:03.862
The model interprets the goal, chooses an action, calls a tool, reads

160
00:08:03.862 --> 00:08:06.242
the real result, and updates its plan.

161
00:08:06.242 --> 00:08:10.479
The loop continues until the task completes, reaches a blocker, or hits

162
00:08:10.479 --> 00:08:11.732
a stopping condition.

163
00:08:11.732 --> 00:08:15.146
The critical question is not how long the model reasons.

164
00:08:15.146 --> 00:08:18.684
It is whether each action produces reliable ground truth.

165
00:08:18.684 --> 00:08:22.511
After a coding agent changes a file, it can run tests.

166
00:08:22.511 --> 00:08:27.011
After a support agent issues a refund, it can read the API response.

167
00:08:27.011 --> 00:08:30.996
After a browser agent clicks a button, it can verify that the page

168
00:08:30.996 --> 00:08:32.203
changed as expected.

169
00:08:32.203 --> 00:08:36.107
That feedback is how an agent knows whether it is making progress.

170
00:08:36.107 --> 00:08:39.979
Customer support and coding are strong agent tasks because they combine

171
00:08:39.979 --> 00:08:43.742
conversation with action and offer relatively clear success criteria.

172
00:08:43.742 --> 00:08:47.088
Autonomy also raises cost and compounds error.

173
00:08:47.088 --> 00:08:50.816
If every step were ninety percent reliable, ten correct steps in a row

174
00:08:50.816 --> 00:08:54.598
would have a theoretical probability of only about thirty-five percent.

175
00:08:54.598 --> 00:08:58.440
Real systems use checks and retries, but the arithmetic makes the

176
00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:02.223
boundary obvious: a longer path cannot rely on confidence alone.

177
00:09:02.223 --> 00:09:06.699
Production agents therefore need sandboxes, permission limits, maximum

178
00:09:06.699 --> 00:09:11.239
iterations, explicit stopping rules, and human confirmation at critical

179
00:09:11.239 --> 00:09:11.751
actions.

180
00:09:11.751 --> 00:09:15.752
They also need a record of tool calls and environment responses so a

181
00:09:15.752 --> 00:09:18.694
failure can be diagnosed, replayed, and recovered.

182
00:09:18.694 --> 00:09:21.386
An agent is not the absence of control.

183
00:09:21.386 --> 00:09:25.224
It gives dynamic decisions to the model and rebuilds control through

184
00:09:25.224 --> 00:09:26.578
feedback and boundaries.

185
00:09:26.578 --> 00:09:30.970
Reversible actions, such as reading information or drafting text, can

186
00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:32.434
receive wider autonomy.

187
00:09:32.434 --> 00:09:36.118
Payments, deletion, and external messages should receive narrow

188
00:09:36.118 --> 00:09:38.223
permissions and pre-action approval.

189
00:09:38.223 --> 00:09:42.108
A practical risk ladder is: automate low-risk actions, inspect

190
00:09:42.108 --> 00:09:46.244
medium-risk actions after execution, and approve high-risk actions

191
00:09:46.244 --> 00:09:47.309
before execution.

192
00:09:47.309 --> 00:09:48.848
Chapter recap.

193
00:09:48.848 --> 00:09:52.694
First, every action must read real environmental feedback.

194
00:09:52.694 --> 00:09:56.848
Second, failure risk compounds across a long execution path.

195
00:09:56.848 --> 00:10:00.774
Third, autonomy requires permissions and stopping conditions.

196
00:10:00.892 --> 00:10:04.880
Even a capable model will fail repeatedly when its tools are difficult

197
00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:05.678
to understand.

198
00:10:05.628 --> 00:10:09.006
Humans need a well-designed interface to use software.

199
00:10:09.006 --> 00:10:12.743
Models need a clear agent-computer interface to use tools.

200
00:10:12.743 --> 00:10:17.222
Tool names must be specific, parameters must be unambiguous, and the

201
00:10:17.222 --> 00:10:21.570
contract should show input formats, boundaries, examples, and edge

202
00:10:21.570 --> 00:10:21.965
cases.

203
00:10:21.965 --> 00:10:24.753
Similar tools need obvious differences.

204
00:10:24.753 --> 00:10:29.154
Errors should state what failed, which input was invalid, and whether a

205
00:10:29.154 --> 00:10:30.022
retry is safe.

206
00:10:30.022 --> 00:10:33.147
Do not make the return format harder than the task.

207
00:10:33.147 --> 00:10:37.411
Forcing a model to place large blocks of code inside heavily escaped

208
00:10:37.411 --> 00:10:39.292
JSON creates avoidable errors.

209
00:10:39.292 --> 00:10:43.166
Return only the information needed for the next decision; dumping an

210
00:10:43.166 --> 00:10:46.984
entire log into context increases cost and hides the useful signal.

211
00:10:46.984 --> 00:10:51.160
Anthropic found that its coding agent often made mistakes with relative

212
00:10:51.160 --> 00:10:51.513
paths.

213
00:10:51.513 --> 00:10:55.474
Changing the tool to require absolute paths made those mistakes much

214
00:10:55.474 --> 00:10:56.522
harder to produce.

215
00:10:56.522 --> 00:10:59.118
So do not optimize only the prompt.

216
00:10:59.118 --> 00:11:03.411
Observe how the model misuses the interface, then change the interface

217
00:11:03.411 --> 00:11:03.840
itself.

218
00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:08.651
Before release, test missing parameters, invalid paths, repeated calls,

219
00:11:08.651 --> 00:11:12.513
timeouts, and recovery behavior, not just ideal examples.

220
00:11:12.513 --> 00:11:14.051
Chapter recap.

221
00:11:14.051 --> 00:11:18.311
First, names, parameters, and boundaries must be clear.

222
00:11:18.311 --> 00:11:22.205
Second, return formats should not create extra difficulty.

223
00:11:22.205 --> 00:11:26.234
Third, design the interface so common errors are harder to make.

224
00:11:26.356 --> 00:11:30.094
For a new task, walk through the architecture ladder in order.

225
00:11:30.044 --> 00:11:34.389
First, can one model call, enhanced with retrieval and examples,

226
00:11:34.389 --> 00:11:35.611
complete the task?

227
00:11:35.611 --> 00:11:40.092
Second, if one call is not enough, can you define the steps in advance?

228
00:11:40.092 --> 00:11:44.111
If yes, prefer chaining, routing, or parallelization.

229
00:11:44.111 --> 00:11:48.260
Third, if the task can be divided but the required subtasks appear only

230
00:11:48.260 --> 00:11:51.006
during investigation, use orchestrator-workers.

231
00:11:51.006 --> 00:11:54.607
Fourth, use an autonomous agent only when the whole path depends on

232
00:11:54.607 --> 00:11:58.477
environmental feedback and the model must keep making its own decisions.

233
00:11:58.477 --> 00:12:02.944
Frameworks can quickly connect model calls, tools, and workflow steps,

234
00:12:02.944 --> 00:12:07.092
but extra abstraction can hide the real prompt, model output, and

235
00:12:07.092 --> 00:12:07.602
failure.

236
00:12:07.602 --> 00:12:11.119
A framework is fine only when you still understand what happens

237
00:12:11.119 --> 00:12:11.900
underneath it.

238
00:12:11.900 --> 00:12:15.698
Before upgrading, save a baseline for the simplest system.

239
00:12:15.698 --> 00:12:20.507
Compare task completion, average cost, latency, and human interventions

240
00:12:20.507 --> 00:12:23.284
on common, difficult, and boundary cases.

241
00:12:23.284 --> 00:12:27.307
Break metrics down by task type so averages cannot hide a critical

242
00:12:27.307 --> 00:12:27.977
regression.

243
00:12:27.977 --> 00:12:31.952
If the complex system does not produce a stable improvement, return to

244
00:12:31.952 --> 00:12:32.861
the simpler one.

245
00:12:32.861 --> 00:12:37.034
Architecture is a measurable iteration, not a one-time declaration.

246
00:12:37.034 --> 00:12:38.573
Chapter recap.

247
00:12:38.573 --> 00:12:42.890
First, test whether one augmented model call can finish the task.

248
00:12:42.890 --> 00:12:46.852
Second, prefer a workflow while the path remains controllable.

249
00:12:46.852 --> 00:12:51.018
Third, let measurable results decide whether to upgrade to an agent.

250
00:12:51.148 --> 00:12:54.059
Remember the complete method in three lines.

251
00:12:54.009 --> 00:12:58.646
If one augmented model call can solve the task, do not build a workflow

252
00:12:58.646 --> 00:12:59.038
first.

253
00:12:59.038 --> 00:13:02.790
If you can draw the execution path in advance, do not build an

254
00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:04.182
autonomous agent first.

